Raymond Barlow &lt;rbarlow@...&gt; wrote:
          Hi Archana,

What you need to do is to break the dependency that you have in this 
code. Instead of getting the connection directly in the code here, 
either call another method to return the connection, or pass it into the 
class on construction. The easiest is to call another method. Something 
like:

public class MyClass {

public ResultSet recentSubmission() throws SQLException {
Connection con = null;
ResultSet rs=null;
try{
Class.forName(&quot;sun.jdbc.odbc.JdbcOdbcDriver&quot;);
con=getConnection()
PreparedStatement ps= con.prepareStatement(
&quot;SELECT SUBMISSSION_GUID FROM SUBMISSION WHERE SUBMISSSION_GUID 
= 143&quot;);
rs=ps.executeQuery();
return rs;
} catch(Exception e) {
e.printStackTrace();
}
//con.close();
return rs; 
}

protected Connection getConnection() {
return DriverManager.getConnection(&quot;jdbc:odbc:acme&quot;,&quot;RIUser&quot;,&quot;Demo&quot;);
}
}

This small refactoring allows us to now create a TestableMyClass where 
we can override the getConnection and return a MockConnection. This not 
only lets you test the class in isolation, but also allows you to test 
this class without having to connect to a real database (big advantage). 
Example:

public class TestableMyClass extends MyClass {

@Override
protected Connection getConnection() {
return new MockConnection();
}

}

Of course you will have to provide an implementation of the 
MockConnection to return the expected values for your test. This might 
be the prepareStatement returning a MockPreparedStatement and your 
MockPreparedStatement then returning a MockResultSet. This will allow 
you to inject the values for SUBMISSSION_GUID in the resultset.

But of course, if you ACTUALLY wanted to hit the database, and test your 
SQL, I would not use junit. I would instead use FitNesse (or 
similar)-but that is my preference. What is it that you are actually 
wanting to test? Your class or the functionality of your database and 
jdbc library?

Regards,
Raymond Barlow

